sample_data.simname: Our Code: We respect one another for Partners
sample_data.section: In and around your home office
sample_data.scenario: Coach: In this first scenario, you and Michael, another Partner in your office are coming back from attending the board meeting of a significant Firm client. Our Firm has been assisting them with the launch of their new go to market strategy. You’re joined by an EM on the engagement, Isobel. Here are Michael and Isobel now. Michael: Thank you both for joining me in there. They’re good clients, and the work we’re doing is having significant impact. Isobel: Yeah, it’s great to see them so passionate about their business. They clearly live and breathe it. Michael: I think what the city is doing is terrible - all these new luxury condos going up are changing the neighborhood and pricing working families out. Have you seen the new housing proposal the city is considering? I’m going to post to my network asking people to oppose the bill and call their council members. Isobel: Yeah, I’m with you, and I respect your commitment, Michael. Michael: Absolutely. Actually, I was drafting a few paragraphs to post to my network, a call to action really, I have a deep network on LinkedIn and want people there to know what I stand for, and better yet, get them contributing to this cause. Could you to take a look before I post? Let me know what you think.
sample_data.choice: I hear you, Michael. I’d be happy to look. My concern would be whether you posting on LinkedIn is too connected to your position as a Firm member. Maybe checking with the External Comms team to make sure that your statement is in-line with our Firm’s policies — before you post anything.
sample_data.feedback: We are expected to communicate responsibly.While we are all entitled to our personal beliefs, it is against Our Code and policies to use Firm resources or technology to advocate for personal causes or share personal political views, except with the appropriate permission.While we all have our opinions, be thoughtful about what you post online especially since the lines between professional and personal are often blurred. We are expected to use good judgement and to consider the impact our online actions have on our own reputation and our Firm’s reputation.If you’re unsure about posting something online or whether our work can be shared more broadly, seek guidance from the External Communications team to avoid unintended consequences. For more information refer to Our Code of Conduct and External Communications Policy.
skills: Acting with integrity and in accordance with Our Code, McKinsey policies, and applicable laws [Overall Performance]

sample_data.section: In and around your home office
sample_data.scenario:
Coach: A few days later, you’re in your home office when Kathryn, a fellow Partner finds you in the kitchenette. Kathryn: Hiya. It’s been a busy week I'm really looking forward to this volunteer activity we’re doing as an office as part of our annual Day of Service.
We’re volunteering with Community Kitchen — the nonprofit we’ve supported for a few years now. And get this, while a bunch of us are going to be packing food into bags for distribution, a group of BAs will get a chance to meet with the executive director. He wants to discuss the org’s five-year strategy with them. Great, huh?
sample_data.choice: That’s a great opportunity. Are you joining them, or do you intend to send another Partner or AP? You also need to check in and get sign-off from our regional Social Responsibility Manager before you go.
